      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum elastic-plastic constitutive model with isotropic hardening is appropriate for Ti-6Al-4V under monotonic quasi-static loading; justified by literature and material coupon data.",
      "rationale": "A bilinear elastic-plastic model with isotropic hardening was adopted for Ti-6Al-4V screw and rod components, consistent with the monotonic quasi-static loading regime of ASTM F1717. Material coupon tensile test data confirmed yield stress and tangent modulus inputs. The UHMWPE vertebral body surrogate was modeled as linear elastic, consistent with prior FDA validation studies. Model form selection is well-supported by literature. Achieved level equals required level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from lot-specific tensile coupon testing; geometric dimensions from CMM measurements of test articles.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus, yield stress, and tangent modulus for Ti-6Al-4V were derived from lot-specific tensile coupon tests performed concurrent with the F1717 bench testing. UHMWPE block dimensions and modulus were measured from the actual test surrogates using CMM and tensile testing respectively. Screw and rod geometry was taken from CAD nominal dimensions with dimensional inspection confirming conformance within ±0.05 mm. Input uncertainty was propagated through the validation metric calculation. Achieved level equals required level."
    },
